// Table
// 
// Tables display collections of data grouped into rows
//
// .basic - A table can reduce its complexity to increase readability.
// .collapsing - By default tables take the size of their container. A collapsing takes up only as much space as its rows.
// .inverted - A tables colors can be inverted
// .definition - A table may be formatted specifically to provide definitions
// .celled - A table may be divided each row into separate cells
// .sortable - A table may allow a user to sort contents by clicking on a table header.
// .padded - A table may sometimes need to be more padded for legibility
// .compact - A table may sometimes need to be more compact to make more rows visible at a time
// .small - A table can also be small
// .large - A table can also be large
//
// Markup:
// <table class="ui {$modifiers} table segment">
//   <thead>
//     <tr><th>Name</th>
//     <th>Status</th>
//     <th>Notes</th>
//   </tr></thead>
//   <tbody>
//     <tr>
//       <td>John</td>
//       <td>Approved</td>
//       <td>None</td>
//     </tr>
//     <tr>
//       <td>Jamie</td>
//       <td>Approved</td>
//       <td>Requires call</td>
//     </tr>
//     <tr>
//       <td>Jill</td>
//       <td>Denied</td>
//       <td>None</td>
//     </tr>
//   </tbody>
//   <tfoot>
//     <tr><th colspan="3">
//       This is the table footer
//     </th>
//   </tr></tfoot>
// </table>
//
// Styleguide 3.10

td
	-ms-word-break 					break-all
	word-break 						break-all

td > a
	display 						block

